Posts: 1410<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/02 8:45:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=410.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sebminas.com/eq/baby.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Let soloing die, lets increase the value of offense</span><hr size=1> Many players are trying to figure out ways to make soloing viable for mages, thinking up new spells or what not. I feel this is not where our collective efforts should be vested.<br>
<br>
1) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant doesn't like it</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
The new expansion was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>purposely</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> designed so pop mobs were largely unsoloable by most classes. They <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>hate</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> soloing, and I don't blame them. It undermines the point of the game. This is a social game based on interdependency.<br>
<br>
If anything, rather than seeing more increases to soloing, you can expect changes like snare starting to break like root when being coupled with distance attacks (such as dots or nukes or archery). <br>
Changes will probably be made to charm as well.<br>
<br>
2) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Its not fair to some classes</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
Why should soloing even exist? Why should a few classes be able to solo, when classes when classes like the 3 pure melees cant? We offer just as much to a group as any rogue or monk does. So do all &quot;solo classes&quot;. <br>
<br>
3) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Just let soloing die</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
Even though it does suck for me as a mage, I'm glad to see soloing dieing. Soloing has always been one of those &quot;things&quot; pointed to by other classes when we asked to be as useful as they were. Now that its no longer there, there is no reason why we shouldn't continue to be as useful of a group member as anyone else. No one can say its overpowered, since we are entirely dependant on a group as we are physically weak, like we as mages were designed to be. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
You might be thinking to yourself, &quot;Ok, you want soloing to die, yet we still are not as valuable to a group as that initial cleric/druid, shaman/enchanter/bard or war/pal/sk. They could give us hundreds of dps, and we still wouldn't be as sought after as they, since that is the nature of an offensive class.&quot;<br>
<br>
My answer? Its time to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>make offense more valuable to a group</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
Everyone knows mages rock for the trial of execution. I get tells literally every day to help with them. Why? Why do they suddenly <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>need</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a mage, when the entire game this wasn't the case? Because unlike in the exping world, there are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>real consequences</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for not having the appropriate dps in the trial. Your party wont succeed if mobs do not die fast.<br>
<br>
As of right now, the only real motivation for anyone taking an offensive class in their group is the desire to make faster experience. We are not actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>needed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to the success of the group.<br>
Despite the fact I am just as dependant on a group as any cleric, enchanter, or shaman, (the later two are actually less dependant, and even clerics can solo undead in pov) no one really <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>needs</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> me, I'm just nice fluff to have around. How is that fair? <br>
<br>
Well, I say its <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not fair</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Its time to have offense work more directly like damage mitigation on exping mobs as was originally intended, to finally give offense that real needed group role. Its time for the trinity to officially die.<br>
<br>
I propose the following change. Enter mob infuriation. The properties of mob ability infuriation are outlined below.<br>
1) Basically, the longer a party is engaged with a mob, the more damage that mob will do.<br>
For example, if you put a 70% slow on a standard exp mob, after 10 seconds it would be a 60% slow, 15 seconds 50% slow, after 20 seconds 40%, so on so fourth. <br>
If the mob is unslowed, then it will be as if the mob is becoming more hasted as the seconds pass. Every interval of increased attack speed is marked to the player with the following message, or something similar:<br>
&quot;A moss snake becomes FURIOUS!&quot;<br>
<br>
2) The timer would be activated upon players being added to the mobs hate list, and it will not be reset by memory blur type spells (to avoid exploits). It will naturally reset itself after 15 minutes of non-engagement, by which the mob would be &quot;calmed down&quot;. This aspect of my change I particularly like, it gives a whole new value to wizards and fast damage in general. No longer can you just pull 4 mobs, and have a shaman drop a slow on them while they stand there idle. No longer can you pull 6 mobs, and have a good enchanter lock them down with no consequences. Fast damage now is important, a class who can speed up the pace of their damage to quickly kill infuriated mobs will be a highly valuable asset to a group, as much so as any mezzer or slower. Slow and mez type spells will still be valuable, however fast damage will be equally valuable.<br>
<br>
How long it would take for intervals between mob infuriation to occur, should of course be entirely dependant on the mob you are fighting. Basically VI needs to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>look</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at the mobs, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>think</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about the levels that should be fighting them, and then decide how long it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>should</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> take to die, assuming 3 of those group spots are occupied by reasonably decent damage dealers of that level. <br>
You shouldn't <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>need</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a mage or a rogue in all 3 of the slots, but you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>should</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have at least 1 or an equivalent, much like in the trial of execution. The other 2 spots should not be filled by a pally and a cleric just because they were &quot;there,&quot; and those spots &quot;don't mean much&quot;. They should be filled by classes who are primarily <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>offense</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. Verant must keep this in mind when deciding how many seconds should pass till the next increment in attack speed. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Here are a few reasons why this is not only a highly desired change, but a needed change:<br>
1) <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Flexible Damage vs Sustained Damage?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
Wizards are the masters of flexible, or fast damage. By this I mean they can control the pace of their damage the best. They can do hundreds of dps, or they can do a few dps. The balancing factor of this power, is their sustained damage is not as good as other offensive classes.<br>
<br>
Sounds good right? Well the problem is, throughout most of eq, there is only a need for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>sustained damage</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in verants environments. Fast damage, although it sounds like a fun role, has <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>almost no value</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> outside of a handful of encounters and situations. So what you have is a class, with a role that verant has created virtually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>no environment</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for, with almost no other abilities to offer since they specialize in it so much. Of course this class is going to be undesired.<br>
<br>
By making offense work more like damage mitigation, the wizard now has real value to a group, and to environments, as much so as any supportive class.<br>
<br>
<br>
2) <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Nukers, Meleers, Doters... whats the difference?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
As I said in #1, sustained damage is the only type of damage anyone really cares about, because verants environment only require sustained damage. Nukers such as wizards measure themselves to a ruler they never were meant to. Sustained damage was never meant to be where the exclusive value of a nuke lies. <br>
This change makes the difference in damage types more  prominent. The optimal group would have the following make up, or something similar: <br>
healer (cleric/druid), <br>
damage mitigation, spell type (enchanter/shaman/bard), <br>
damage mitigation, tank type (war/pal/sk), <br>
damage, support type (wizard/druid/mage), <br>
damage, hybrid/sustained type (rogue/monk/ranger/necro/beastlord)<br>
damage, hybrid/sustained type (rogue/mage/monk/ranger/necro/beastlord)<br>
<br>
Notice every class is included, every class has a defined role. Thats how it should be. May the trinity RIP.<br>
<br>
<br>
3) <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Damage mitigation vs Healing?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
Thott is a very vocal critic of the power of damage mitigation relative to healing. I agree with him to an extent, if you can almost completely circumvent the damage a mob is doing, what value does the healer have other than in rare emergency situations? If slow were to become less powerful relative to its environment as per my suggested changes, healing would again retain its intended value.<br>
<br>
This doesn't mean classes like enchanters and shaman are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>less valuable</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, not at all, if anything they would be more desirable since mobs do more damage. Slow still has a powerful effect, the difference between an unslowed and a slowed mob would still be relatively as considerable as it is now. However, healing would now have a more equal effect.<br>
<br>
<br>
4) <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Where is the challenge, where is the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fun</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
Find a camp. Pull endless stream of mobs to the camp with no risk of dying. Ding 65. BORING. The game needs to be made more challenging, the game needs to be made more fun. Right now, the optimal way to make experience is in very low risk grouping situations which has the player in a vegetative state single pulling mobs till they ding 65. While this new change wont solve all or even most of those inherent design flaws with the everquest grouping system, it will add a new level of challenge to it, which in turn will make grouping more fun. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Everyone wins</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> with this change, healers, damage mitigation classes, and damage dealing classes alike.<br>
<br>
Thoughts? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sargonnis>Sargonnis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/02 9:22:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=410.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Interesting Idea</span><hr size=1> While i do like the idea in some ways, it as far as i can tell will not help mages the most.<br>
<br>
Personally, i do not see how this will help a mage as much as say a rogue ( high sustained DPS ).  The mage is restricted by mana while a rogue is not.  In a chain pulling situation ( most exp groups ), the fact that we can go oom would be a problem.  The group could be better served by a rogue, who would not run out of mana and would keep an equal or very nearly equal damage output.  I dont see this helping wizards at all.<br>
<br>
I think your execution analogy, while somewhat similar is innaccurate.  In the execution trial, you need only operate for 4 waves that last no more than 2 minutes each ( ~10 minutes, with the breaks and such ) and the boss, which you do not even need mana for.  Thus, while we truly shine there, in an exp group situation we would have to keep the same DPS over an hour long period ( probably more ).<br>
<br>
While i think your idea does definitely seem a step in the right direction, and i find it very interesting, i do not think it will accomplish what you wish for.  I do not, however, have any better idea and iot would certainly help a bit, just not nearly as much as it would help rogues, and maybe even monks.  This probably does not apply to those with FT 15 and whatever other forms of mana regen lots do not have access too. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sargonnis>Sargonnis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/02 9:23:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=410.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   bleh</span><hr size=1> I cannot seem to edit my post, but wanted to also reply to the fun section.  Perhaps the idea should be implemented just on those grounds, as it would be more fun hehe.  And thats it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sambus>Sambus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 171<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/02 9:24:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=410.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.shiftclick.net/eq/sigs/60x60tinker.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Let soloing die, lets increase the value of offense</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The other 2 spots should not be filled by a pally and a cleric just because they were &quot;there,&quot; and those spots &quot;don't mean much&quot;. They should be filled by classes who are primarily offense. Verant must keep this in mind when deciding how many seconds should pass till the next increment in attack speed. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think it's a creative suggestion, but I also think it really cripples groups that are already less-than-optimal.  Consider this extremely common scenario: it's an off night in your guild, and there are 2 druids, 1 mage, a paladin, and a bard LFG.  Well, you have healers and a tank, bard slow/CC, and some dps, but this group will have a very obvious disadvantage against mobs that become gradually hasted over time (or un-slowed over time).  They don't have the dps to kill faster, and while they may have the healing to cover the increase in damage, their downtime will be much greater due to the druid's lesser heals.  Currently, at least with the bard's marginal slow and the druid's marginal CH, they can still manage to keep up a fair pace.  Not optimal, but fair.<br>
<br>
It also does very little or nothing to eliminate the cleric dependency.  If the mob's damage increases exponentially, so does the healing power required.  Slowers actually help mutt groups by knocking out at least one of the &quot;trinity&quot; (cleric), often times two (cleric &amp; warrior) because it makes it easier for lesser tank classes to handle the job.  You say you want the trinity to die, but by gradually hasting mobs or having slow wear off, what you're doing is locking down yet another slot or two for a nuker/dps class.  That's great if you're a nuker like we are, but it sucks to be the bards, paladins, and other lower-dps classes of the world, whose potential to get in a group just dropped to 2/6ths instead of one half.<br>
<br>
Like I said, it's creative, but I think you're overlooking some pretty major drawbacks (or, inconveniences).  I think you've also forgotten the natural tendancy for EQ players to seek out the most optimal group configuration for the situation.  If mob dps starts to increase exponentially over the duration of a fight, it will lead even more groups to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>require</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the right tools to handle the new challenge, which is still the &quot;holy trinity.&quot;  And those people who are LFG on experience night are still left LFG. <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dark-bane.com/mageloframes/sambusframe.htm">Sambus Veneficus</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Arch Mage of Ak'anon, 63<br>
Member, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dark-bane.com">Dark Bane</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Mithaniel Marr Server<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=archangelranari@themagicianstower>Archangel Ranari</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/02 9:58:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=410.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Let soloing die, lets increase the value of offense</span><hr size=1> Noonie definitely has a point, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>however no one ever had a problem with soloing until Verant decided to put the best experience spots in the game in three friggin zones (exaggeration). </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Secondly, Verant has changed around the roles of a lot of classes so many times that people no longer what they created their class for.  Paladins are now masters of quick heals.  After 2 years, Magicians are back to where they originally were as masters of utility damage.  Clerics have gained considerable offensive power and can now solo.  Druids have gone from a utility class to a nuking class and now a primary healing class with their new CH.  Just dumb stuff like that.  People created Necros, Druids, Wizards, and Mages to solo when they want to.  Now Verant doesn't want them to.  <br>
<br>
What gives?<br>
<br>
Thirdly, EQ is just unbalanced.  Verant is sitting on their ass with revamping old, useless zones, because they know people will be forced to buy PoP just to expand any further.  Hey guys, what a concept!  <br>
<br>
I'm all for companies making profits.  That's what allows me to own my 5.0 Mustang, take my girlfriend out to dinner, and buy stuff when I need to.  I'm not for changing the original concept of a game, the one that drew so many followers to begin with, for purely money making reasons.  <br>
<br>
I mean, for crying out loud.  Look at companies such as Enron.  Can we say Nvidia with it?  Don't people realize, and this is a far out statement, that with all this corporate greed maybe, just maybe, another 'French Revolution' may be on its way around?  <br>
<br>
