le.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This would work as long as the whole function of 'social' mobs and level aggro are removed to prevent unwanted adds. Otherwise there will be a lot of 'unfair' called when something adds, enrages while mezed and proceeds to plow through the group like a bulldozer due to having to deal with the first mob they INTENTIONALLY pulled.   I like the idea, but current game mechanics would make quite a few zones totally unplayable because of constant adds.<br>
I honestly can't think of an alternative to prevent this problem for 'honest' adds but it would most certainly prevent groups from hogging spawns by pulling multiples and parking them nearby.<br>
<br>
I also have an idea of my own. Larger groups.  Increase the single potential group size to 8 or 10. This would make for extra 'whatever we can find' slots and still allow for the 'optimal' group of 6 or less. Many times I've logged on and found nothing but full groups. had they been slightly larger then there would have been a potential for at least one or two open spaces. (Or fewer larger and all full groups. Depends on how you view it) <br>
<br>
<br>
The only real way to get people to stop soloing and start grouping is to give better group XPs than solo XPs. It's that simple. Increase the group bonuses and give an XP penalty for not being grouped and you'll see it happen a LOT faster. The only reason I solo anymore is to farm or because I can't find a group. If solo Xps were (and I really hate to use this term but it applies) nerfed, MANY more groups would form just out of necessity. OR.. in lieu of this method, change the way experience is awarded in groups. Keep the current group bonus, but award experience as if you yourself had killed the mob for each person.<br>
<br>
example:<br>
<br>
level 35 Druid kites a single level 30 mob in approximately 3-4 minutes. (unsure of the exact time, but this is what I've been told by Druids that I know) It dies, the Druid receives 1000 XPs<br>
<br>
Group consisting of:<br>
35 Warrior, 35 Cleric, 35 Magician, 35 Druid, 35 Necromancer and 35 Wizard (I don't know the exact bonus for a full group, but for my example it will be 30%)<br>
Kills level 30 mob in approximately 1 minute. It dies, the group receives a total of 7800 XPs (Each character receiving 1300 or 1000   30% group bonus)<br>
<br>
Now.. Who would want to solo anymore? The only reason I could think of is wanting all the loot for yourself or farming. (and who farms anything above light blues anyway?)<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>1) Verant doesn't like it.<br>
The new expansion was purposely designed so pop mobs were largely unsoloable by most classes. They hate soloing, and I don't blame them. It undermines the point of the game. This is a social game based on interdependency.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If this were actually true, then why is it possible to solo at all? Also, why did they remove the 50% xp penalty for pet classes if they didn't out damage their pet when soloing? This seems to me that they WANTED us to be able to solo more effectively. I can't believe that they DON'T want soloing to exist. I think it's more like they just favor grouping. The problem is the bone wasn't big enough. Before PoP and after the pet XP fix, I made better XPs soloing than I EVER did grouping but I don't play to watch the number above my name increment, I play to have fun with my friends and meet new people. I HATE soloing, but after being forced to either solo or sit LFG for hours at a time, I chose soloing and just talk to my friends between their groups pulling mobs in the hopes that something will open up.<br>
<br>
